class Solution {
public:
    string robotWithString(string s) {
        string t;
        string ans;
        for (char c : s) {
            t += c;
            t.push_back(c);
            sort(t.begin(), t.end());
            while (!t.empty() && t[0] <= c) {
                ans += t[0];
                t.erase(t.begin());
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n^2)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: MEDIUM
explanation: This solution uses a greedy approach, maintaining a sorted string t that represents the characters that can be appended to the result string. It iterates over the input string s, appending each character to t and sorting t. If the first character of t is less than or equal to the current character in s, it appends the first character of t to the result string and removes it from t. This approach ensures that the result string is lexicographically smallest. However, the time complexity is O(n^2) due to the sorting operation inside the loop, which may not be efficient for large inputs.

